<font color="#FF0000">A ROUGH ONE TO FIGURE</font><br>
<tt>Tue Nov 18  1:13:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I'm feeling a bit low today, feeling that I should be getting on a plane tomorrow for D.C. and the ceremony for Jolly 365.  I could have, but I couldn't have, gone.  I have some committments, but none I couldn't have posponed if I had decided to.  But I decided not to, to stay close to family, continue my job search quest, and not go for Wednesday's ceremony.  It will be a big one, and I would have seen people I hadn't seen for many years, but I can't go even though I probably could have gone.  Making sense? <br><br>
It would have been nice to see Al Avery again, but he's not there.  His relatives will finally have their peace, and I will send flowers, but I won't be there.  Al's remains, what's left, will be buried in Arlington at 11:00 am on Wednesday.  People will talk about his life, and his wife and kids will know a bit more about him.  <br><br>
In a way, I wish I had made the decision to go; in a way, I know that I shouldn't go.  I knew Al, but ours was more an acquaintance than a friendship.  He was there when I got to DaNang, and he stayed well beyond when I left.  He loved the mission, the contribution he was making, and the life.  I loved the contribution, but there were other things which really bothered me about Vietnam and how we fought the war.  I worked to get out--Al worked to stay there.  Now I'm here, with my family, and they will have ceremonies for Al on Wednesday.  I should be there; I should stay here.  This is a rough one to figure.
